04764nam a22005775i 9780674984837DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749848377 a10.4159/97806749848372doi  a(DE-B1597)500400  a(OCoLC)1032071117  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aJC574b.M84 2018eb 7aPOL0420202bisacsh04a324.2/17091821223  aMG 103602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122815:121141 aMudge, Stephanie L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLeftism Reinvented :bWestern Parties from Socialism to Neoliberalism /cStephanie L. Mudge. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (410 p.) :b3 halftones, 37 graphs, 9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables and Figures -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tAnalyzing Leftism’s Reinventions -- tFrom Socialist, to Economistic, to Neoliberalized Leftism -- tThe Genesis and Infrastructure of Socialist Leftism -- tEuropean Leftism’s First Reinvention -- tEconomistic Leftism, American-Style-or, Making the Democrats “Left" -- tInterdependence in the Making of Leftism’s Second Reinvention -- tNew Economists, New Experts, New Democrats -- tMaking Western European Leftism “Progressive” -- tConclusions and Implications -- tMethodological Appendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeft-leaning political parties play an important role as representatives of the poor and disempowered. They once did so by promising protections from the forces of capital and the market’s tendencies to produce inequality. But in the 1990s they gave up on protection, asking voters to adapt to a market-driven world. Meanwhile, new, extreme parties began to promise economic protections of their own—albeit in an angry, anti-immigrant tone. To better understand today’s strange new political world, Stephanie L. Mudge’s Leftism Reinvented analyzes the history of the Swedish and German Social Democrats, the British Labour Party, and the American Democratic Party. Breaking with an assumption that parties simply respond to forces beyond their control, Mudge argues that left parties’ changing promises expressed the worldviews of different kinds of experts. To understand how left parties speak, we have to understand the people who speak for them. Leftism Reinvented shows how Keynesian economists came to speak for left parties by the early 1960s. These economists saw their task in terms of discretionary, politically-sensitive economic management. But in the 1980s a new kind of economist, who viewed the advancement of markets as left parties’ main task, came to the fore. Meanwhile, as voters’ loyalties to left parties waned, professional strategists were called upon to “spin” party messages. Ultimately, left parties undermined themselves, leaving a representative vacuum in their wake. Leftism Reinvented raises new questions about the roles and responsibilities of left parties—and their experts—in politics today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLiberalismxEconomic aspectsxWestern countries. 0aLiberalismxEconomic aspectszWestern countries. 0aLiberalismxWestern countries. 0aLiberalismzWestern countries. 0aPolitical partiesxWestern countries. 0aPolitical partieszWestern countries. 0aRight and left (Political science)xWestern countries. 0aRight and left (Political science)zWestern countries. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Conservatism & Liberalism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978067498483742